{"source_key":"sha256-a74ceb5e1c9633ab993c14c11d587d71","record_index":15,"record_hash":"sha256:be23d2179f9c24274496c67805d595e74b28e8e993792ead1fc56389aaf22414","timestamp":"2026-05-20T19:01:40.950Z","kind":"tool_result","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:function_call_output","role":null,"text":"Chunk ID: eae454\nWall time: 0.0000 seconds\nProcess exited with code 0\nOriginal token count: 2800\nOutput:\n# Agent Session Handoff Design\n\nThis note sketches the handoff feature that sits above the `but-agentlog`\nprimitives. It is intentionally not an implementation contract yet.\n\n## Goal\n\nLet a developer continue work from one machine, agent, or provider session in\nanother machine, agent, or provider session.\n\nThe target experience:\n\n1. work happens on a branch with agentlog capture enabled\n2. GitMeta sync moves captured agentlog data with the repository metadata\n3. another machine checks out or switches to the branch\n4. the user asks an agent to catch up\n5. the agent uses GitButler commands to discover and read relevant prior session\n   context\n6. the new agent continues with enough context to be useful, without pretending\n   it has natively resumed the old provider session\n\nThis is contextual handoff, not exact provider-native replay.\n\n## Current Building Blocks\n\nThe primitive layer can already provide the facts a handoff flow needs:\n\n- durable project-scoped sessions\n- capture turns within sessions\n- ordered transcript records within each turn\n- environment observations for each turn\n- GitMeta sync of the stored data\n- verified lookup of sessions related to a branch, review, or change\n- bounded hydration of related turn windows\n\nThat is enough to design an agent-facing workflow without adding product-shaped\nstate to `but-agentlog`.\n\n## Current Data Feasibility Check\n\nLooking at the live GitMeta database for the `agentlog-turn-storage` branch on\n2026-05-20, the proposed tools are realistic, but the data shape confirms that\nthey need to be bounded and metadata-heavy.\n\nObserved data:\n\n- 14 sessions related to the branch\n- 29 related turns\n- 7,357 stored transcript records\n- the largest main session has 16 turns and 6,037 records\n- the initial backfill turn in that session has 5,371 records\n- hydrating the largest session locally is fast enough for now, roughly 217ms\n- returning that session as full timeline\n[TRUNCATED]\n[REDACTED:entropy])\n- [GitLab system notes](https://docs.gitlab.com/user/project/system_notes/)\n- [Gerrit Change-Ids](https://gerrit-review.googlesource.com/Documentation/user-changeid.html)\n- [git trailers](https://git-scm.com/docs/git-interpret-trailers.html)\n\nThe lesson is to use stable ids and structured links. Handoff should preserve\nthe relationship between branch, review, change, session, and turn evidence, but\navoid heavyweight supply-chain attestation machinery in v1.\n\n## Research Takeaways\n\nThe handoff feature should copy these ideas:\n\n- branch/worktree-aware discovery\n- named or previewable sessions when we have names/previews\n- resume/fork/reference as separate concepts\n- compact outlines before full transcript reads\n- derived summaries as conveniences, not truth\n- stable ids and links across rebases or branch movement\n- reindexable derived stores if we add local acceleration later\n\nIt should not copy these:\n\n- provider-native resume semantics for cross-provider handoff\n- automatic ingestion of all related transcript records\n- persistent generated summaries as the only source of truth\n- one magic `handoff` command that hides the read path\n- cryptographic provenance or SLSA-style ceremony for v1\n\n## Minimal Tool Draft\n\nThe minimal agent-facing surface should be three read tools:\n\n```text\nbut agentlog sessions [branch [<branch>] | review <review> | change <change>] [--limit N]\nbut agentlog timeline <session-key> [--limit N]\nbut agentlog records <session-key> --turn <turn-key> [--from start|end|<index>] [--limit N]\n```\n\nThis is enough for an agent to:\n\n1. discover prior sessions\n2. orient itself in the session and turn structure\n3. read bounded transcript records only where needed\n\nThere should not be a first-class `handoff` command. Handoff is the workflow the\nagent performs with these tools.\n\nIf `branch` is provided without a branch name, it should mean the current branch.\nThat keeps the common prompt easy:\n","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-20T19:01:40.950Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"function_call_output","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]"}}}